{"id":"2108.03451","submitter":"Pablo S. Cornaglia","authors":"D. J. Garcia, V. Vildosola, A. A. Aligia, D. G. Franco, Pablo S.\n  Cornaglia","title":"Magnetic properties of chiral EuIr$_2$P$_2$","comments":"12 pages, 18 figures, to appear in Physical Review B","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1103/PhysRevB.104.214411","report-no":null,"categories":"cond-mat.other","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We present a minimal model that provides a description of the magnetic and\nthermodynamic properties of \\Eu. The model contains two exchange coupling\nparameters, which are calculated using Density Functional Theory, and a local\neasy axis magnetic anisotropy term. The classical ground state of the system is\na generalization of the well known 120$^\\circ$ structure observed in triangular\nantiferromagnets. Monte Carlo simulations show two phase transitions as a\nfunction of the temperature. With increasing temperature, the system\ntransitions from the ground state into a high-entropy collinear\nantiferromagnet, which in turn at higher temperatures presents a second order\ntransition to a paramagnetic state. A high enough external magnetic field\nparallel to the anisotropy axis produces a spin-flop transition at low\ntemperatures. The field also reduces the temperature range of stability of the\ncollinear antiferromagnet phase and leads to a single phase transition as a\nfunction of the temperature. The reported behavior of the specific heat, the\nmagnetization, and the magnetic susceptibility is in agreement with the\navailable experimental data. Finally, we present the magnetic phase diagrams\nfor magnetic fields parallel and perpendicular to the easy axis.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sat, 7 Aug 2021 13:55:10 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 23 Aug 2021 11:46:03 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 25 Nov 2021 09:59:01 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-12-22"}
